TI  - INTEGRATING SATELLITE IMAGERY AND ELEVATION MODELS FOR DEGRADATION/REGENERATION ANALYSIS OF AN AMAZONIAN MANGROVE FOREST
T2  - IGARSS 2024-2024 IEEE INTERNATIONAL GEOSCIENCE AND REMOTE SENSING SYMPOSIUM, IGARSS 2024
CP  - IEEE International Geoscience and Remote Sensing Symposium (IGARSS)
AB  - The Amazon Macrotidal Mangrove Coast harbors the world's largest mangrove belt, spanning 7,590 km (2), with the Braganca Peninsula (Brazil) being a focal area for mangrove changes due to the 1970s construction of road PA-458. This road altered tidal channels, causing a 2 km mangrove degradation buffer. Using remote sensing and digital elevation models, this study analyzed degraded areas. The mid-resolution data between 1986 and 2019, showed a reduction of degraded areas of 247.96 ha. High-resolution data from 2003 to 2019 indicated a 211.65 ha decrease of the degraded areas. High-resolution classifications achieved >0.9 accuracies, with Avicennia germinans dominating due to saline resilience. Digital models highlighted regeneration in lower areas, forming saline lakes toward PA-458. Sea-level rise triggered mangrove re-establishment, influenced by "La Nina" and "El Nino" precipitation extremes.
