TI  - Relationship analysis between forest evolution and declivity using Landsat images
T2  - NATIVA
AB  - This study aimed to analyze the evolution of forest cover and its relationship with the declivity in the city of Agudo, RS, Brazil, between the years 2010 and 2014. We used Landsat 5 satellite images, for the year 2010, and Landsat 8 images, for the year 2014, in order to produce the mapping of the use and coverage of the land, through MaxVer classification, thus generating four classes: "Forest", "Agriculture/Livestock", "Exposed Soil" and "Water". The declivity map was generated from SRTM radar data (Shuttle Radar Topography Mission), with the production of four declivity classes: less than 15 degrees, between 15 degrees and 30 degrees, between 30 degrees and 45 degrees and more than 45 degrees. The SPRING 5.1.8 application was used for data processing. With the purpose of quantifying the transition between the classes of use and coverage of the land, we used the LEGAL programming (Spatial Language for Algebraic Geoprocessing). Then, we held the intersection between the declivity map and the forest evolution map. From the obtained results, we found that approximately 70% of the study area has declivity less than or equal to 15 degrees, thus indicating the predominance of flat lands, mildly wavy and wavy, in the municipal territory. Agriculture and livestock are predominant in these areas, whilst forests are predominant in bigger declivities, but the forest regeneration was greater in areas with declivity of up to 15 degrees, totaling an increase of 2,611.11 ha. Therefore, one should realize that forest areas are increasing and occupying areas that were formerly occupied by agriculture or livestock.
