AU  - James, PE
TI  - TRENDS IN BRAZILIAN AGRICULTURAL DEVELOPMENT
T2  - GEOGRAPHICAL REVIEW
AB  - The traditional agricultural system of Brazil is based on speculative gain and invested in monoculture. This is marked by 4 periods: (1) sugar period of 16th and 17th centuries; (2) gold and diamond mining of 18th century; (3) coffee planting of the 19th century terminating in 1930; (4) speculation in rubber, cacao, oranges, sisal, etc. The basic support of rural settlement is pasturing of cattle. The terrain is hilly to mountainous. Current trends indicate that in spite of an increasingly rapid migration from rural districts into expanding cities, the rural population has continued to grow. Crop production has risen but the productivity of the individual rural farm worker is low, and declining because of the persistent use of manual implements. Agriculture is thus wasteful, inefficient and costly. When production drops the land is abandoned to pasturage. With the destruction of tropical forest closest to urban markets by exploitative practices, there is a continued rise of food prices due to transportation costs. The traditional system of land rotation is destroying a large part of the virgin areas, and the end of uncut tropical forest is in sight. Scientific farming has been demonstrated in Brazil, but since there are no speculative profits, little capital is invested. Application of the principles of scientific agriculture might change the pattern of cultivation. Although scientific farming is feasible and will increase productivity and lower the cost of food production, it will decrease population in thinly centered areas and make for a further concentration in the already densely populated places.
